    value: 전국 시대에 굴원(屈原)은 왕을 간(諫)하다가 쫓겨나서 자살하였다.
english:
  title: A Memorial of Gratitude Presented from Gwangju
  author: Yun Eon-i
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Last in the month of the fifth year of Byeong-chin, I received an impeachment through the commander-in-chief's memorial, and by imperial decree lost my position, receiving instead the office of Defense Inspector of Liang Province. I departed at once. After passing through the year Mu-o, by imperial grace I was appointed Governor of Gwangju, Commandant of Cavalry and Provisions, Inspector of the National Academy, and Attendant Counselor of the Court of Rites. The Ministry of Rites urged my appointment. By the twelfth month of Gyeong-shin, I presented myself at court and the appointment was confirmed. Now I am already in office. Six years have I sat idle, resigned to death a thousand times over. Yet now, receiving the imperial mercy in a single day, it is as though I have been born anew. I look up to heaven speechless, place my hand upon my breast and weep. Thus I offer my gratitude.

    I reflect that when superiors govern those below, they always desire loyalty, and when ministers serve their lord, they seek to earn trust. Yet this cannot always be secured, and sometimes lord and minister grow estranged. The Duke of Zhou could not escape false rumors. The Marquis of Jiang could not avoid imprisonment. Though Xiao Wangzhi was the Emperor's preceptor, he drank poison in the end. Though Qu Yuan was of royal blood, he drowned himself in the river. If even the sage-worthy fall thus, what hope for one as lowly and insignificant as I?

    I, whose nature is crude and whose disposition is rigid, lack the wisdom to preserve even myself—how could my learning adorn a kingdom? In youth I was fortunate to receive my father's grace and pass the examination of the Worthy and Capable. Later, through circumstance, the imperial court elevated me to high office. At times I participated in affairs of state and frequently attended the royal lectures. In my foolish ambition, thinking myself favored by fortune, I grew careless with worry. Whenever an issue arose, I spoke without consideration of consequences, heedless of right and wrong, alive or dead. The elders shook their heads at this, and the younger generation marked me for censure. Slanders and intrigues were woven into accusations. Impeachments rose again and again, and some deemed me worthy of death.

    Though the benevolent king perceived my straightforwardness, he could not resist the chorus of voices. Thus was I exiled to a distant place to preserve what remained of my life. Yet on the evening I received my banishment, as I departed, I knew not the source of my crime—only deepening sorrow filled my heart. When at last I read the commander-in-chief's memorial, it stated: "Eon-i formed with Ji-sang a deathless pact, consulting together on all matters great and small. During the western campaign of the year Im-ja, he petitioned to establish an era name and the imperial title, and seduced the students of the National Academy to present this matter, seeking thereby to provoke the anger of the Great Jin, to exploit circumstances and implement his designs through factional allies, plotting unlawful rebellion—the acts of no true minister." When I read this three times over, at last my heart found peace.

    For first, the petition to establish an era name arose from sincerity in honoring the ruler. Our own dynasty has precedent in the ages of Taejo and Gwangjong. Though Silla and Bohai established era names, the great powers never mobilized troops against them, nor did smaller states dare criticize their error. How then should this sagely age deem it presumption? Second, though the charge speaks of forming deathless pacts and provoking the Jin—words great indeed—the beginning and end do not align. If powerful enemies invaded our realm, would we not exhaust ourselves in defense? How then could we exploit circumstances? Who are these factional allies alleged? What persons were to be destroyed? When the multitude lacks harmony, battle brings defeat, and one finds no place to stand—how could I scheme freely? Moreover, I never participated in the great discussions, my accord with Ji-sang was not predetermined, and my role in other appointments—all this the imperial majesty has clearly perceived.

    Since my fall to the rivers and lakes, six cycles of cold and heat have passed. My stipend long ceased. Clothing and food became scarce. Old friends severed their bonds. My wife and children lost their home. My frame grew withered like a dead branch. My spirit wandered as one in drunken dreams. That I have lived until now owes all to imperial knowing.

    I reflect again: that I, of weak constitution, served in the western campaign, forgetting myself to defend the realm—this was but my duty as a subject. That all success came through others' efforts—what merit is mine to speak of? Now that I venture to speak, I do not presume to claim achievement, only to offer what little sincerity I possess and humbly beg the imperial heart to take one glance.

    In the year Yi-myo, the commander-in-chief made a strategy of depleting the enemy's provisions. Yet the rebels did not surrender, time wore on, and the river ice melted with no recourse in sight. In the third month, I alone proposed constructing earthwork barriers, but others opposed me and it was not adopted. By the eleventh month, the commander-in-chief began construction at Yangmyeong Gate, ordering me and others to inspect in rotation. Calculating the accumulation of earth, in months we would reach the city walls. I consulted with the forward commander on fire assault, and had the official An Jeong-su craft five hundred loads of fire implements. On the ninth day at dawn, using stone cannon fashioned by Zhao Yan, we fired—flames like lightning, size like carriage wheels. Though the enemy first came to extinguish them, by evening the fire grew intense and could not be quenched. Through the night we fired. The Yangmyeong Gate, its galleries—some twenty structures—and the earthen mounds the enemy had raised were utterly consumed.

    On the twelfth day, the enemy completely broke, and passage opened for our forces. I went at once to report to the commander-in-chief and urged that we strike while the moment held, lest the enemy prepare defenses. Some protested vehemently, and I too grew angry in dispute. On the fourteenth, I went again to the forward position to urge immediate assault. All said, "Wait until the earthworks are complete before attacking." The enemy held fast behind wooden palisades. I pleaded for immediate attack, but still no decision came. On the sixteenth, the commander-in-chief gathered the officers of all five commands to deliberate. All maintained their prior view. That very day, the enemy constructed inner walls—circumstances now forced action without delay.

    Before this, Chi Seok-sung, overseeing construction, had agreed with me, and later Deputy Commander Yi Yu, Official Wang Su, and seven others joined in support. Thus did the commander-in-chief finally adopt our plan. On the nineteenth, dividing forces into three routes, we advanced—like splitting dry bamboo, without impediment. That day I controlled the central force with officials Shin Ji-chung and Kim Jeong-hwang, General Kwon Jung-gyun, Fang Zi-shou, Clerk Lim Moon-byeok, and Park Ui-shin. We quietly prepared our troops, reaching Chilseong Gate at dawn. We piled wood and set fire. As flames rose, the enemy stirred in panic but could not respond. We burned ninety-seven structures of gates and galleries. It seemed we could advance directly, yet heaven grew dark with rain. We withdrew to camp.

    At dawn the next day, enemy leaders Jeong Deok-hwan, Yu Wi-hou, and four minor officials slipped from the city. Fang Zi-shou had them captured and brought to camp. I sent Deok-hwan and Wi-hou to the commander, while sending General Kim Seong-gi with two captured officers to Gyeongchang Gate to persuade the enemy. General Hong Gyeol came forth and surrendered. That day the forward force at Guangdeok's Hamwon Gate still faced resistance, but Gyeol consulted with the righteous people, seized the false commander Choi Young, and brought two companies to our side.

    Thereafter, enemy generals Su Hwang-rin, Jeong Seon-gok, Park Eung-so, and some ninety officers, civil and military, came in succession to surrender. The lesser rabble numbered beyond counting. I sent Fang Zi-shou with troops to guide Li Jeong-jeong and the defected Seo Hyo-gwan to enter the city and seal the palace, granaries, and treasuries. I had Jeong-jeong guard the palace and deliver the keys—six or seven bundles—to the commander.

    But I learned that the left force, entering through the north gate, had loosed troops to plunder the great treasury of wealth and silk. I sent Park Ui-shin to stop them, but they would not listen. I sent Kwon Jung-gyun again, and only then was the treasury preserved. I sent my son Yang to report to the commander-in-chief with the true date. The commander-in-chief then came to the central force and ordered Li In-shil and Li Shik to seal the palace, granaries, and treasuries, and thereupon we presented a memorial with the full account.

    Such is the general outline, difficult to recount in detail. At that time I believed I had made small service to the realm. How then, thereafter, did false charges suddenly assail me, casting this foolish one into injustice? I reflect that my former misdeeds are indeed my own fault.

    I humbly read the memorial Su Shi presented when degraded. He wrote: "When I served as governor of Xuzhou, the river flooded the city nearly to collapse. Day and night I defended against it and by fortune achieved safety. I also selected the person Cheng Fei from the people of Yizhou and had him capture rebels, thereby seizing the insurgent sorcerer Li Duo, Guo Jin, and sixteen others. Perhaps merit and fault might cancel out." Yet Su Zhai, with all his brilliance, still needed to offer such explanation. How much more must I?

    Though I languished long in difficulty, dare I not speak and seek redress? Moreover, Kim Jung was questioned by magistrates yet within seven months returned to high office. Chu Chung was exiled to Jiangnan yet within three years recovered his former post. Only I, unworthy and at odds with the world, had my name entangled in harsh law, while all competed to spread loose slander. Years have passed with no resolution of my case. Though I did not spare myself from seeking death to prove my heart, truly the sagely lord's kindness I cherished. Long I bore shame in silence, preserving this remnant life while awaiting vindication.

    Unexpectedly now, the imperial grace extends great magnanimity. Taking pity on my utter destitution, pitying my undivided heart, the sovereign repeatedly sent ministers to counsel and instruction, raising my solitary loyalty anew from distant exile. Gradually I am embraced by the new transformation and stand among the common folk. At last my evil name is washed clean, and I look to final redemption.

    This flows from supreme benevolence that knows no boundary and profound virtue that embraces all things—extending mercy even to the humble beasts, unwilling to cast away even sandal and hairpin. In that hour when all men's anger surged, you preserved my remnant years. Through long years of wandering, you gathered my wasted frame. By special grace, you granted me true office and restored my former stipend.

    False charges dissolve as the sun emerges and the roof grows bright. This withered and rotting frame revives as spring returns and rain descends. Surely I am not mere wood or stone, insensible. How could I fail to recognize heaven's and earth's transforming grace? My vigor has waned—no longer do I mirror my former self. Yet my crimson heart remains, sworn to exhaust my remaining years in service. Though I should fill a ravine, let me never forget the kindness that binds me to eternal gratitude.
